BT 0 g /F2 16 Tf 70.08000000000001 600 Td (Chapter 2: The 50/30/20 Rule Explained) Tj ET
q 0 G 1 w 60 585 m 372 585 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 560 Td (The 50/30/20 rule is the simplest budgeting framework ever created.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 538 Td (Fifty percent of your after-tax income goes to needs like rent and food.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 516 Td (Thirty percent goes to wants like entertainment, dining out, and hobbies.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 494 Td (Twenty percent goes to savings and debt repayment above minimums.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 472 Td (Needs are things you must pay: housing, utilities, insurance, groceries.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 450 Td (Wants are things you enjoy but could live without temporarily.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 428 Td (The savings category includes emergency fund, retirement, and extra debt payments.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 406 Td (If your needs exceed 50 percent, look for ways to reduce housing or car costs.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 384 Td (This rule works as a starting point but adjust percentages to your situation.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 362 Td (Someone with high debt might do 50/20/30 with more going to debt.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 340 Td (The key insight: pay yourself first by automating savings before spending.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 318 Td (Track your spending for one month to see how your current habits compare.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F1 10 Tf 213.6 30 Td (2) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
