BT 0 g /F2 16 Tf 96.96000000000001 600 Td (Chapter 3: Tracking Your Income) Tj ET
q 0 G 1 w 60 585 m 372 585 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 560 Td (Write down every source of income you receive each month.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 538 Td (Include your primary job salary or wages after taxes are taken out.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 516 Td (Add side hustle income, freelance work, or gig economy earnings.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 494 Td (Include investment dividends, rental income, or interest payments.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 472 Td (Count child support, alimony, or government benefits you receive.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 450 Td (For irregular income, calculate your average monthly earnings over six months.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 428 Td (Knowing your exact take-home pay is the foundation of any budget.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 406 Td (Many people overestimate their income by confusing gross and net pay.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 384 Td (Net pay is what actually hits your bank account after deductions.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 362 Td (If paid biweekly, remember you get two extra paychecks per year.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 340 Td (Update your income tracking whenever you get a raise or lose income.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 318 Td (Accurate income tracking prevents you from budgeting money you do not have.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F1 10 Tf 213.6 30 Td (3) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
