BT 0 g /F2 16 Tf 73.92000000000002 600 Td (Chapter 7: Building an Emergency Fund) Tj ET
q 0 G 1 w 60 585 m 372 585 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 560 Td (An emergency fund is money set aside for unexpected expenses only.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 538 Td (Start with a goal of one thousand dollars as your starter emergency fund.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 516 Td (Then build toward three to six months of essential living expenses.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 494 Td (Keep emergency money in a high-yield savings account separate from checking.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 472 Td (This prevents you from accidentally spending your safety net.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 450 Td (Emergencies include job loss, medical bills, car repairs, and home fixes.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 428 Td (Sales, vacations, and new gadgets are not emergencies.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 406 Td (Automate weekly or biweekly transfers to your emergency savings account.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 384 Td (Even twenty-five dollars per week builds to thirteen hundred in a year.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 362 Td (Having an emergency fund prevents you from going into debt when life happens.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 340 Td (Sixty percent of Americans cannot cover a four hundred dollar emergency.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 50 318 Td (Your emergency fund is your financial foundation. Build it before investing.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F1 10 Tf 213.6 30 Td (7) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
